1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,980
 and we're hoping that with this fleet we can speed up the pace of digitization. And this is particularly exciting to me because some of these books haven't been opened like a hundred years. So there's just a lot of, I think, profound Catholic insight that's just not accessible to people right now. And as we get into these libraries and we digitize it, it becomes accessible. It's incredible. I mean, think when we digitize a work here in the hub, and I should acknowledge that the Alexandria Digitation Hub has been on pilot with the Pontifical Oriental Institute for us.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:50,920
 over a year now. So they were instrumental in getting the hub off the ground. What's incredible to me is that we'll be able to scan a few books a day, probably more than that. And the minute those books are finished scanning and they get processed, the contents of those books are made available to anyone in the world, on any device, in their native language immediately.

3
00:00:56,920 --> 00:00:57,920
 Good morning, Matthew.

4
00:00:57,920 --> 00:00:58,920
 Good morning.

5
00:00:58,920 --> 00:01:14,920
 So today what we want to do is we want to start to kind of unpack some of the history of Longbeard and find out where it kind of all began and, you know, the team as it is now, and then some of the bigger projects as we look into that horizon.

6
00:01:14,920 --> 00:01:23,920
 So, Matthew, here we're in Rome. I know that you were in Rome for a bit of time a few years ago and, you know, have spent a lot of time in Rome.

7
00:01:23,920 --> 00:01:29,160
 Can you share us a little bit the origin of Longbeard? How did, how did, how did the mission start?

8
00:01:29,160 --> 00:01:39,920
 Well, I mean, I remember pitching a bunch of the guys, many of whom would come to join us in my apartment in Toronto.

9
00:01:41,920 --> 00:01:54,720
 I didn't really know much about business at all or entrepreneurship. At the time I was working at the Archdiocese of Toronto and I started my career there working in the Office of Spiritual Affairs.

10
00:01:56,080 --> 00:02:04,320
 We kind of dealt with a lot of doctrine questions and kind of canonical questions and things like that. And so they brought me in to help kind of fix up the office, help it run a little bit more efficiently.

11
00:02:04,320 --> 00:02:14,640
 That was a great experience. And I mean, one thing it certainly did is made me aware of the innumerable, you know, doctrinal issues that the priests have to kind of cover off.

12
00:02:15,600 --> 00:02:22,140
 And, and of course, you know, I've been a seminarian for a time, so I had some sense of this, but I didn't, I didn't fully appreciate the enormous demands on them for that.

13
00:02:22,140 --> 00:02:28,420
 And so when I was working there, we see a lot of calls, sometimes people asking doctrinal questions, sometimes people putting complaints.

14
00:02:29,260 --> 00:02:39,040
 I need an exorcism kind of, kind of questions, you know, stuff all over the place. And, you know, we, and we had to respond. And so we had, you know, and often that resulted in us going to primary sources, right?

15
00:02:39,040 --> 00:02:43,600
 And then having to compose an email and respond. And this, this ate up a lot of our time, as you can imagine.

16
00:02:43,600 --> 00:02:51,760
 So that, that's kind of, I think, where the genesis of, of kind of the idea of MatterStream I started is there's got to be a more efficient way to do this.

17
00:02:51,760 --> 00:02:58,160
 Later on, I was, I moved on to the, into the special projects office and I ran that for a while.

18
00:02:58,160 --> 00:03:06,780
 And one of the tasks I had was, was helping to get the world and the church to be more in active kind of dialogue with each other on, on important issues.

19
00:03:06,780 --> 00:03:10,600
 So, I mean, one of the first projects was helping bring Steubenville conferences to Toronto.

20
00:03:10,600 --> 00:03:13,620
 And so that was fun because that was, you know, how do we engage young people?

21
00:03:13,620 --> 00:03:17,580
 And, you know, and, and of course, Steubenville conferences had been very successful at that point.

22
00:03:17,580 --> 00:03:20,680
 And so they, they were trying to do a more effective job of engaging young people in the diocese.

23
00:03:20,680 --> 00:03:23,140
 So bringing Steubenville conferences up to Toronto just seemed to make sense.

24
00:03:23,140 --> 00:03:27,880
 That posed enormous challenges and particularly like how do we leverage technology to effectively engage young people?

25
00:03:28,160 --> 00:03:31,760
 And encourage them to come and try this thing, this new thing for a lot of them, Steubenville conferences.

26
00:03:31,760 --> 00:03:44,000
 Some of the other events we did, we started something called the Chesterton Debate Series, which was, which was trying to get, you know, basically topics that are, let's say like atheism, modern atheism, and trying to get a dialogue with the world on about it.

27
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:50,000
 And I remember one of the first ones we did was, was a priest of the oratory in Toronto, or the oratory St. Philip Neary.

28
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:55,440
 And he was debating the head atheist for Canada or something like that, head of the atheism society, whatever it was called.

29
00:03:55,440 --> 00:03:57,520
 And I remember just loving that debate.

30
00:03:57,520 --> 00:04:00,620
 And I think exactly, that's what I wish I could see more of, right?

31
00:04:00,620 --> 00:04:04,400
 Where we bring our best, they bring their best, and we just let the ideas go head to head, right?

32
00:04:05,740 --> 00:04:08,020
 So we did a few other events along those lines.

33
00:04:08,020 --> 00:04:20,460
 And so I kind of got excited at the prospect of finding, leveraging technologies and using that, because you were using YouTube and things like that to distribute this content, using technology to help bring the faith into contact, direct contact with the world.

34
00:04:20,460 --> 00:04:25,560
 And at some point I realized that this really required more focused energy and effort.

35
00:04:25,560 --> 00:04:33,440
 So that's when I decided it probably is the time to leave the archdiocese and try and focus on this specifically.

36
00:04:33,440 --> 00:04:35,400
 And this goes back to the whole pitching in the apartment.

37
00:04:35,400 --> 00:04:40,220
 So, you know, I knew some guys, but I didn't know a lot about, you know, technology per se.

38
00:04:40,220 --> 00:04:47,060
 I was just more of a user of it, and I'd come to appreciate its usefulness, but I didn't technically know how to build stuff.

39
00:04:47,060 --> 00:05:04,480
 So I pulled together a bunch of people, most of them were in kind of the engineering world, some in the design space and things, and said, hey, what if we were to actually come together and kind of create some kind of agency in order to help build technology and ensure it's used more effectively for the purposes of primarily evangelization?

40
00:05:04,480 --> 00:05:09,080
 And what kind of shocked me at that meeting is that everyone said, okay, let's do this.

41
00:05:09,080 --> 00:05:14,740
 So, I mean, not everyone could leave, you know, leave their full-time jobs right away, but everyone kind of started investing their time and energy into it.

42
00:05:14,740 --> 00:05:16,640
 And so that's essentially where Longbeard started.

43
00:05:16,860 --> 00:05:24,420
 And we started initially just building websites and technology platforms for Catholic organizations growingly.

44
00:05:24,420 --> 00:05:27,160
 It started in Canada and then expanded to the U.S.

45
00:05:27,160 --> 00:05:28,960
 And then eventually, and then eventually expanded to Rome.

46
00:05:28,960 --> 00:05:32,080
 And so I had to do some more consulting work here.

47
00:05:32,080 --> 00:05:34,520
 And so I was traveling between Toronto and Rome, you know, fairly often.

48
00:05:34,520 --> 00:05:43,020
 Initially, the client that actually brought us here initially was the Gregorian University Foundation, which later on become a very close partner of ours.

49
00:05:43,540 --> 00:05:51,220
 And then while I was here, I realized that there was a lot of organizations here that needed the kind of help that basically the problem we were trying to solve.

50
00:05:51,220 --> 00:05:52,960
 It was very poignantly.

51
00:05:52,960 --> 00:05:57,140
 I made aware to me that there was a lot of opportunities here.

52
00:05:57,140 --> 00:05:58,520
 There were big challenges.

53
00:05:59,520 --> 00:06:01,660
 And I realized I was traveling too much.

54
00:06:01,660 --> 00:06:06,320
 And so eventually, it just kind of made sense for us to kind of move our headquarters here.

55
00:06:06,320 --> 00:06:10,100
 And so we made that decision almost like seven years ago now.

56
00:06:10,100 --> 00:06:15,780
 And then very soon, so we started doing some work with the Pontifical Universities and other Catholic organizations around the world.

57
00:06:16,040 --> 00:06:22,940
 And then eventually, I met, at the time, Father Michael Czerny, who was working at the Dicastery for Integral Human Development.

58
00:06:22,940 --> 00:06:30,280
 And he proposed that the Pope, migrants and refugees, is a big important issue for the Pope.

59
00:06:30,280 --> 00:06:35,740
 And he let it, you know, to me that the Pope wants to know more about this issue.

60
00:06:35,740 --> 00:06:50,040
 And he wants to, he wants to ensure that the effort that's being, that the effort that he's going to be supporting is, is leveraging all the cutting edge tools possible to ensure that they're as effective as, as, as, as one, as, as possible, you know, be as effective as they could be.

61
00:06:50,040 --> 00:07:05,380
 And, and so Father Michael Czerny and then Father Michael Fabio Baggio, now, but now both cardinals, said, why don't we work with you and why don't you come in and help us set up this technological infrastructure for the Pope's new migrants and refugees section.

62
00:07:05,380 --> 00:07:10,140
 And so that was our, I was our first big project of working with the Holy See directly.

63
00:07:10,140 --> 00:07:12,300
 And, and it was a really exciting project.

64
00:07:12,300 --> 00:07:21,900
 I mean, in large part, because I just, when I, when they asked me in the meeting, what would you, you know, what would you do if you were setting technological infrastructure for, for an office and that, well, how would you set it up?

65
00:07:21,900 --> 00:07:25,680
 And I, and I said, well, I mean, that's, that's not a very complicated question.

66
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:28,760
 I mean, I mean, Fortune 500 have a pretty typical stack that's working well.

67
00:07:28,760 --> 00:07:35,020
 So I proposed, you know, the, the, the, the typical stack at the time, but I, I just kind of back of my mind, I was thinking, but this is never going to happen.

68
00:07:35,020 --> 00:07:42,180
 I mean, you'd have to get approval from Vatican IT department and not to say that they wouldn't be excited about the prospect, making some, you know, adding some new technologies to stack.

69
00:07:42,180 --> 00:07:43,160
 It's complicated, right?

70
00:07:43,160 --> 00:07:46,420
 But they said, eventually I got the call and I said, let's do it.

71
00:07:46,820 --> 00:07:51,380
 And I, and I realized, well, when the Pope's running at running something right directly, that helps a lot.

72
00:07:51,380 --> 00:08:04,680
 So, so, so we did, we went in there and we ended up partnering with Google on that project to help bring in this technological infrastructure to help facilitate, basically help them collaborate with, with parties around the world to serve the issue of migrants and refugees.

73
00:08:04,680 --> 00:08:13,080
 And Matthew, what did it do to come, you know, from Toronto, from Canada, where, you know, there's a, there's a real high level of technological innovation.

74
00:08:13,080 --> 00:08:14,080
 There's a lot of stuff.

75
00:08:14,080 --> 00:08:19,400
 And to come to the eternal city where, you know, at least the reputation is that things move at a slower pace.

76
00:08:19,400 --> 00:08:26,100
 You know, the, the Vatican has this great vision, but times technologically, it's, it's oftentimes a little bit behind.

77
00:08:26,100 --> 00:08:28,400
 What did, what did you, what did you see the church's needs there?

78
00:08:28,680 --> 00:08:30,580
 What did it illuminate more clearly for you?

79
00:08:30,580 --> 00:08:35,560
 That I think there's, the people that are here are very eager to do more.

80
00:08:35,560 --> 00:08:40,120
 I mean, obviously they're all here because they, they care about, you know, Christ, right.

81
00:08:40,120 --> 00:08:41,320
 And, and evangelization.

82
00:08:41,320 --> 00:08:44,000
 And they want to ensure that Christ is proclaimed the four corners of the earth.

83
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:56,700
 I think that a lot of the problems that the, I'll say the Vatican, but really, you know, the Holy See encounters and the other pontificate universities and stuff are a lot, are very similar challenges that a lot of old, you know,

84
00:08:56,700 --> 00:08:59,120
 I'd say like governmental, like biocracies have, right.

85
00:08:59,120 --> 00:09:06,460
 It's these technology changes very frequently, which requires a lot of retooling and reeducation of the staff.

86
00:09:06,460 --> 00:09:10,080
 And, and that can, sometimes that can take that kind of change management can take a while.

87
00:09:10,080 --> 00:09:13,620
 And so it's, and for some reasons, you know, sometimes things just lose steam, right.

88
00:09:13,620 --> 00:09:17,260
 And by the time you've, you've trained a staff on one piece of tech and next one's out.

89
00:09:17,260 --> 00:09:17,820
 Right.

90
00:09:17,820 --> 00:09:19,140
 And then it goes, well, what's the point?

91
00:09:19,140 --> 00:09:23,360
 So, I mean, I, and I should say like, it's not, they weren't all the same.

92
00:09:23,360 --> 00:09:24,980
 Some of them were at, were at different levels.

93
00:09:25,340 --> 00:09:31,760
 So there are some Vatican, you know, dicasteries that are very sophisticated in the use of technology and, and others, which are, which are just starting to understand it.

94
00:09:31,760 --> 00:09:35,780
 So part of that, I think is just a lot of the consistent kind of down to leadership, right.

95
00:09:35,780 --> 00:09:40,820
 How, how important is the person who's in charge of that particular dicastery field technology is in order to serve their mission?

96
00:09:40,980 --> 00:09:45,420
 So I think it like the last like 10 years, it's become increasingly clear.

97
00:09:45,420 --> 00:09:46,600
 They have to leverage it more effectively.

98
00:09:46,600 --> 00:09:47,300
 It's just how.

99
00:09:47,300 --> 00:09:52,200
 So, so that, that's, that's the first thing is good, goodwill, good intentions.

100
00:09:52,200 --> 00:09:57,060
 It's just this, this is, it's difficult here as it would be with any, any big organization.

101
00:09:57,060 --> 00:10:04,560
 I think the, the other part that's, that's a bit kind of complicating is, I mean, the Vatican works in a lot of different languages, right.

102
00:10:04,560 --> 00:10:15,180
 So, you know, whenever you're building a tech platform, you have to start thinking about, okay, how's that platform going to work, you know, in, in around the world, especially when you, when you're servicing people at different, uh, different language groups.

103
00:10:15,360 --> 00:10:19,820
 And so that, that's difficult from like, if you have, you know, there are various offices, which are parallel to the world, right.

104
00:10:19,820 --> 00:10:23,680
 We see now you're handling change management, not just for Rome, but you're handling change management globally, which is challenging.

105
00:10:23,680 --> 00:10:25,980
 And then also the users of these technologies as well.

106
00:10:25,980 --> 00:10:31,760
 So again, that's not a problem that's, that's, um, non-typical for like a large Fortune 500 company.

107
00:10:31,760 --> 00:10:38,040
 Um, uh, but I would say it's, it is a little bit more, if you think of it like a government bureaucracy is a little bit more rare, right.

108
00:10:38,040 --> 00:10:45,560
 So, I mean, you have the United Nations and organizations like that, which, which, which reach fairly far, but not many governments have that unique global challenge.

109
00:10:45,560 --> 00:10:48,660
 So that just, that's, that makes it just harder, but it's not impossible.

110
00:10:48,660 --> 00:10:49,560
 Wow.

111
00:10:49,560 --> 00:10:59,420
 So Matthew, so you're, you're here in Rome, you're working with the, uh, with, with Father Chang at the time in the, in the migrant, the decryptor for, for integral human development and specifically with the migrants and refugees section.

112
00:10:59,780 --> 00:11:02,120
 Um, you're, you're, you're building this technological infrastructure.

113
00:11:02,120 --> 00:11:19,520
 When did, um, when did you realize, you know, with, with the, with the innovations taking place in AI, with that space, you know, making more and more, um, you know, tides and ripples, uh, that you felt like, oh, wow, this is something that I need to, you know, then eventually pivot completely towards.

114
00:11:19,520 --> 00:11:28,020
 Well, I think like most people, Hollywood did a good job of priming, priming me for why AI one day could be really important.

115
00:11:28,020 --> 00:11:28,300
 Right.

116
00:11:28,300 --> 00:11:38,140
 I think all of us, like with many technologies, we're just kind of waiting for the technology to be further enough along that actually it's, it's gonna be practically useful or, or be practically capable of changing the world.

117
00:11:38,140 --> 00:11:46,700
 And so I think when we, when we started doing some work with Google and I saw how they were using AI under the hood, I got impressed with, with how they were leveraging it.

118
00:11:46,700 --> 00:11:51,180
 But, you know, it's, um, machine learning, you know, classic machine learning thoughts.

119
00:11:51,180 --> 00:11:54,820
 It, that takes, you know, you gotta be a pro to, you know, how to do that stuff well.

120
00:11:54,820 --> 00:11:55,060
 Right.

121
00:11:55,060 --> 00:11:55,960
 And you need lots of data.

122
00:11:55,960 --> 00:12:00,460
 And I just didn't see any practical way for it to be leveraged, um, yeah, at the, at the time.

123
00:12:00,460 --> 00:12:04,120
 So really it was a kind of a democratization issue, right?

124
00:12:04,120 --> 00:12:09,740
 How do we democratize the technology and make it a little bit, little bit less difficult, um, to use and implement?

125
00:12:09,940 --> 00:12:12,820
 And it wasn't really until Chachupiti dropped.

126
00:12:12,820 --> 00:12:17,840
 I mean, that was kind of the moment for me when I realized, wow, okay, hang on this, this, this is different, right?

127
00:12:17,840 --> 00:12:20,100
 This AI could be extremely useful.

128
00:12:20,100 --> 00:12:24,300
 And, and so then, then, then it kind of like, it harkened back.

129
00:12:24,300 --> 00:12:26,740
 I mean, when I saw it being used and I found out Catholics were using it, right?

130
00:12:26,740 --> 00:12:27,900
 Asking a philosophical more questions.

131
00:12:27,900 --> 00:12:32,300
 I realized, okay, the technology is great, but there's obviously some problems with it that need to be mitigated.

132
00:12:32,380 --> 00:12:35,680
 I mean, the hallucination when it comes to like church doctrine is a big deal, right?

133
00:12:35,680 --> 00:12:38,680
 I mean, you don't want, you don't want the thing making, making up church doctrine and leading people astray.

134
00:12:38,680 --> 00:12:39,980
 This is, this is about people's souls.

135
00:12:39,980 --> 00:12:42,700
 So the enormity of that kind of hit me.

136
00:12:43,700 --> 00:12:48,200
 But then, then I thought back to when I was back in, you know, in the chancery, the Archdiocese, right?

137
00:12:48,200 --> 00:12:55,460
 And, and I thought to myself, man, if I was working at the Archdiocese and I could just ask this chap on anything and it would, it would go to the sources and give me the answers.

138
00:12:55,460 --> 00:12:57,980
 And I thought, wow, I mean, that, that could be transformative.

139
00:12:57,980 --> 00:13:02,820
 And then when I started thinking about, well, what if, what if that could be able to anyone in the world, right?

140
00:13:02,820 --> 00:13:05,020
 So this isn't just a tool for priests and for chanceries.

141
00:13:05,020 --> 00:13:08,740
 This is, this is something that in principle, anyone could use.

142
00:13:09,320 --> 00:13:15,680
 I realized it was worth, it was worth, you know, making a run at it to see, see if we could, we can make it work for, for the Catholic church.

143
00:13:15,680 --> 00:13:24,520
 And so we started, it was a research project at the time called Magisterium AI to see how far we could go in kind of mitigating the downsides.

144
00:13:24,520 --> 00:13:27,220
 So how, could we effectively reduce hallucinations?

145
00:13:27,220 --> 00:13:31,800
 How do, how do we ensure that the answers that it's producing are aligned, right?

146
00:13:31,800 --> 00:13:32,860
 And, and are, and are relevant.

147
00:13:32,860 --> 00:13:38,600
 How do we ensure there's greater transparency when, when the AI is generating?

148
00:13:38,600 --> 00:13:50,460
 I mean, right now, you know, when you ask a chat to be a question, it, it'll generate an answer typically from its, you know, based on, based on its training data, which, you know, it consists of, I'm sure some church documents, but also, you know, Reddit posts and things like that.

149
00:13:50,460 --> 00:13:54,620
 And, and so, and so, you know, you get a Catholic answer, it may sound good, right?

150
00:13:54,620 --> 00:13:56,340
 But how do you know, how do you know it's faithful?

151
00:13:56,340 --> 00:14:04,460
 And so that's why for us, we built MatterStream AI, we knew that everything that our AI said has to be grounded in sources in the same way perplexity was approaching this in a very similar manner.

152
00:14:04,460 --> 00:14:08,820
 So, so how do we ensure that everything the AI says is grounded in, in primary sources?

153
00:14:09,500 --> 00:14:14,240
 And, and that way it helps the AI to, to ensure that everything it's saying is aligned because it has a source to reference.

154
00:14:14,240 --> 00:14:18,600
 And also for the people, they can have confidence knowing that what the AI is saying is true.

155
00:14:18,600 --> 00:14:23,840
 And if, and if they don't, if they think something sounds wrong, they can check the source and see why it's said.

156
00:14:23,840 --> 00:14:27,780
 And, and anyway, so that, so that, that was like, that was, that's what began the project.

157
00:14:27,780 --> 00:14:40,060
 And we found that, we found that if you, with the right combination of prompt engineering, you know, citations and tools that you could, for the most part, mitigate hallucinations.

158
00:14:40,060 --> 00:14:43,720
 Hallucinations are always a reality, but you could significantly reduce them, reduce them.

159
00:14:43,720 --> 00:14:48,920
 And that's when we realized when we, when we scaled this out and let it kind of out into the world and we got great feedback that this is something worth investing.

160
00:14:49,440 --> 00:14:54,460
 Well, and Matthew, can you share a little bit about the, the team that, you know, the, behind the scenes that's working on this?

161
00:14:54,460 --> 00:15:01,340
 When you, when you first launched Magisterium AI to the public, how many, how many documents was it sourcing?

162
00:15:01,340 --> 00:15:09,620
 Well, when we initially released it for kind of private testing, this is where we were trying to work with the archdiocese and candidates and things to test the project just to make sure.

163
00:15:09,620 --> 00:15:10,520
 I think we only had 600.

164
00:15:10,520 --> 00:15:19,880
 I mean, we had, we had the big ones, like the catechisms, the compendiums, the code of canon law, you know, it's up to the primary, some encyclicals, things like that.

165
00:15:19,880 --> 00:15:22,600
 The stuff that we, that most people would have on their shelves.

166
00:15:22,600 --> 00:15:24,660
 And we thought that's a good place to start.

167
00:15:24,660 --> 00:15:28,060
 But what was the, what was the response like at first?

168
00:15:28,060 --> 00:15:29,300
 It was good.

169
00:15:29,300 --> 00:15:37,840
 I mean, so, you know, the short story, when it came to when we kind of like, we're supposed to be like privately, quietly launching it for the purpose of expanding the testing group.

170
00:15:37,840 --> 00:15:45,380
 The story is, at the time we released it, we ended up, I ended up agreeing to an interview with EDPTN.

171
00:15:45,380 --> 00:15:46,980
 I think it was like News Nightly or something.

172
00:15:46,980 --> 00:15:53,940
 And, and I, and I said yes to the interview, but hindsight, that probably was not a good idea.

173
00:15:53,940 --> 00:15:57,420
 And I should have waited because after the interview, it went viral.

174
00:15:57,420 --> 00:16:06,480
 And then we got so much traffic, it actually crashed us and we couldn't get back up again because we were exceeding all the rate limits of the LLM we were using.

175
00:16:07,040 --> 00:16:10,220
 And so we actually, at the time, ChatGPT was the one we were using under the hood.

176
00:16:10,220 --> 00:16:14,300
 So we actually had to go directly to Sam Altman and appeal for help.

177
00:16:14,300 --> 00:16:17,740
 And, and he responded and he, and he stepped up pretty quickly to help us out.

178
00:16:17,740 --> 00:16:24,380
 And, and that was, that was in large part thanks to Father Philip Luray, who's been a collaborator on us on Matters from R.I. since the very beginning.

179
00:16:24,380 --> 00:16:26,360
 So, I mean, I mean, it's, it's, it's ironic, right?

180
00:16:26,360 --> 00:16:31,900
 That if it wasn't for Sam Altman, I don't know if Matters from R.I. would have been here today because I don't think we would have been able to get back up.

181
00:16:31,980 --> 00:16:34,020
 At the time, they were very compute constrained.

182
00:16:34,020 --> 00:16:38,200
 There's only so much inference compute to them and ChatGPT exploded and they, they weren't expecting it.

183
00:16:38,200 --> 00:16:42,080
 And so they were, they had to kind of rate limit a lot of people, people are using their API.

184
00:16:42,080 --> 00:16:45,180
 And so for us, we weren't an enterprise client, so we weren't going to get priority.

185
00:16:45,360 --> 00:16:50,460
 So if he hadn't stepped in to do that, I don't think we would have been able to get up, get back online for, I don't know how long.

186
00:16:50,460 --> 00:16:55,120
 And, and that's what I was really concerned about is, is, is we knew we still had a lot more work.

187
00:16:55,120 --> 00:17:02,040
 Do you imagine how it wasn't perfect, but we still felt it was better than some of the other products have been put out there that, which basically we call a wrappers.

188
00:17:02,040 --> 00:17:09,860
 You put like a kind of a user interface on top of ChatGPT and you call it Catholic, but because it wasn't referencing the primary documents and things,

189
00:17:10,040 --> 00:17:14,760
 and they weren't really dealing with the hard problems of hallucinations and, and things.

190
00:17:14,760 --> 00:17:20,300
 And so, and so, you know, when those apps came out and people tried them and they hallucinated, well, it didn't, didn't look good.

191
00:17:20,300 --> 00:17:20,580
 Right.

192
00:17:20,580 --> 00:17:23,880
 And it was, it was kind of damaging for the Catholic AI ecosystem.

193
00:17:23,880 --> 00:17:29,460
 So, so I, I was, because we were trying to move more slowly and, and trying to do this right.

194
00:17:29,460 --> 00:17:36,920
 I, I, I was really important to me that we continued to work and that, and so I think it's him stepping in at a, at a huge impact.

195
00:17:37,220 --> 00:17:39,400
 And Matthew, can you break it down?

196
00:17:39,400 --> 00:17:48,820
 How does Magisterium AI differentiate in, in, in theory and also in practice with regards to the other major LLMs and then also the other Catholic alternatives?

197
00:17:48,820 --> 00:17:51,060
 Yeah, it's a good, it's a good question.

198
00:17:51,060 --> 00:17:58,760
 So in large part, it just, it just comes down, well, one, to the objectives of the systems themselves, right?

199
00:17:58,760 --> 00:18:05,360
 So, so, so ChatGBT and Gemini and Claude and, and Plexity, their objective function, as we say in the industry.

200
00:18:05,360 --> 00:18:08,620
 So their purpose is, is not to, is not fidelity, right?

201
00:18:08,620 --> 00:18:10,720
 I mean, they're not optimizing on those benchmarks.

202
00:18:10,720 --> 00:18:14,460
 And so, you know, they can often do a good job of representing church teaching.

203
00:18:14,460 --> 00:18:18,360
 I think they're getting very good at it, at it nowadays, but they're not perfect.

204
00:18:18,620 --> 00:18:29,180
 And, and because they, they don't, they don't benchmark for it, it is one of these areas, especially in like long form conversations where we start asking questions about a more obscure church teaching and things like that is they, they won't have a lot of data on it necessarily.

205
00:18:29,180 --> 00:18:31,020
 And they will have a propensity to hallucinate.

206
00:18:31,580 --> 00:18:33,700
 So, so that, so that, that's an issue.

207
00:18:33,700 --> 00:18:37,480
 And then there's a question of what, when they do go for sources, what sources are they, are they using?

208
00:18:37,480 --> 00:18:46,000
 I mean, are they using the right sources or are they just doing a web, web search and, you know, grabbing stuff from, from, from websites and things, which sometimes may work and sometimes it doesn't.

209
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:46,260
 Right.

210
00:18:46,260 --> 00:18:48,860
 So, so that, that, that's another, another issue.

211
00:18:48,860 --> 00:18:54,040
 You know, and the other is just, I would say, I talked about how their objectives are not fidelity.

212
00:18:54,040 --> 00:19:03,220
 I mean, and one of the major problems I think with a lot of these LMs is, is they're, they're more and more optimizing for user engagement, which one would expect because that's how they generate revenue.

213
00:19:03,220 --> 00:19:06,680
 And so that can often lead to this, we call sycophancy, right?

214
00:19:06,680 --> 00:19:20,960
 Where they're, they're trying to kind of keep you engaged and therefore they have this disposition to tell you what you want to hear, which, which makes sense in a, in a lot of use cases, but not, not when you're, you're querying a Catholic church teaching.

215
00:19:21,760 --> 00:19:23,980
 So, so those are two reasons.

216
00:19:23,980 --> 00:19:44,700
 And the other, other primary one where we saw particular issues was when they were asked questions about like complex documents or, or spiritual resources that you have, you, where you can't just like memorize all, all the, all the content and just regurgitate it and make sense of it.

217
00:19:44,700 --> 00:19:47,160
 Like a good example would be the divine office.

218
00:19:47,660 --> 00:19:52,060
 If someone were to ask me, I want to pray to the divine office today, Jachipides, give me the divine office.

219
00:19:52,060 --> 00:19:56,360
 You know, it may have the divine office in its, it may have trained on it, right?

220
00:19:56,360 --> 00:20:03,820
 So it may be in its, in its, in its neural net, maybe in its parameters there, but retrieving it and organizing it and putting it out in a way that makes sense and is accurate.

221
00:20:03,820 --> 00:20:05,660
 It just is not, it's not effective at that.

222
00:20:05,940 --> 00:20:19,940
 So we realized that a large part of our work, in addition to expanding our knowledge base relentlessly was about building these proprietary tools that are, I should say specialized tools, not proprietary, specialized tools that would allow the right context to be served to the models, right?

223
00:20:19,940 --> 00:20:27,440
 So if someone did ask for the principal device or someone we're working on right now, a better example would be of the readings of the day, which is something that's currently in matters for me.

224
00:20:27,440 --> 00:20:30,640
 It knows, it knows the location of the person.

225
00:20:30,640 --> 00:20:36,140
 It therefore knows, it knows the date and therefore it can select the right readings and make sure that those readings are, are provided to the model.

226
00:20:36,600 --> 00:20:38,880
 And, and that way the model has, has the right context.

227
00:20:38,880 --> 00:20:46,200
 And so, you know, as users of interacting, we become painfully aware of, of all kinds of ways LLMs are just kind of limited.

228
00:20:46,200 --> 00:20:52,880
 And whenever we, we come across one of those limitations, we, we see if we can, we can develop some kind of tool to ensure, to help the LLM commit to the right answers.

229
00:20:52,880 --> 00:20:54,320
 Well, that's extraordinary.

230
00:20:54,320 --> 00:21:05,420
 And Matthew, in terms of, of education, like I can imagine the Magisterium AI would be the perfect tool to accompany students, teachers through, through a course, through a classroom, through knowledge base.

231
00:21:05,420 --> 00:21:12,040
 How do you see Magisterium AI, you know, impacting and integrating itself into the Catholic education model?

232
00:21:12,040 --> 00:21:17,320
 Well, I, I think we're already starting to see how AI is being integrated into the education space.

233
00:21:17,320 --> 00:21:22,320
 I mean, I think, you know, I'm thinking every teacher is probably painfully aware of how much their students are becoming to rely on AI.

234
00:21:22,320 --> 00:21:26,220
 And, and so I don't, I don't think that necessarily is a bad thing.

235
00:21:26,220 --> 00:21:35,220
 I, obviously we don't want, you know, people kind of outsourcing all their, you know, critical thinking skills to, to large language models.

236
00:21:35,220 --> 00:21:39,860
 But, but I, I don't think that's, I don't think that that's gonna, that's how it's gonna play out.

237
00:21:39,860 --> 00:21:43,680
 I, I think in the end, what it'll probably, I think people were curious by nature.

238
00:21:43,680 --> 00:21:47,900
 And so as long as we were presented with the right questions to ask, I think people are gonna ask them.

239
00:21:47,900 --> 00:21:56,480
 And, and I think outsourcing to an LM to kind of give them a, give them a, you know, to bring the right context to bear and can be helpful on a journey.

240
00:21:56,480 --> 00:22:02,340
 And so I don't think that people's, fundamentally, I don't think people's questions are ever gonna stop, provided they're, they know the right questions to ask.

241
00:22:02,360 --> 00:22:08,500
 And so I, I think what I'll just do is just allow people to kind of work through a lot more, a lot more than they used to be able to do, right?

242
00:22:08,500 --> 00:22:14,340
 I mean, when we think about like a hundred years ago, if I had a profound philosophical question, I would have to hope my priest could cover it off.

243
00:22:14,340 --> 00:22:16,620
 And if he couldn't, I have to go find a philosopher, right?

244
00:22:16,620 --> 00:22:21,400
 Which means I'd probably have to go to a university and just, you know, or ask, go to a library, right?

245
00:22:21,400 --> 00:22:22,160
 And dig through books.

246
00:22:22,160 --> 00:22:25,040
 I mean, I mean, so that's a lot of what we say in the industry, friction, right?

247
00:22:25,040 --> 00:22:27,320
 It's hard work to get that answer.

248
00:22:27,320 --> 00:22:28,920
 And to think now, right?

249
00:22:28,920 --> 00:22:38,960
 To think now, all I have to do is go to a mastermind, ask the question, and then it queries more and more, almost everything the church is like set up, set on the topic, retrieves those documents.

250
00:22:38,960 --> 00:22:42,480
 Then the AI reads them all and then presents me an answer with the citations.

251
00:22:42,480 --> 00:22:43,300
 That's incredible.

252
00:22:43,300 --> 00:22:44,360
 That's incredible.

253
00:22:44,360 --> 00:22:49,060
 So I just don't see long-term how that is going to truly hurt him here in humanity.

254
00:22:49,580 --> 00:22:55,880
 Again, provided we know why we're meant to exist and what life's about, and therefore we know the right questions to be asking.

255
00:22:55,880 --> 00:23:01,040
 I think in the end, it'll just encourage people to ask more questions, and I think that that actually will further academics.

256
00:23:01,040 --> 00:23:08,500
 If you were to say to me, like, as far as vision goes, how do I think AI will play an important role in Catholic education?

257
00:23:08,500 --> 00:23:19,280
 I think one of the ways that we're, one of the things that we're kind of calculating around is how much value would there be for a student if they had like a private tutor?

258
00:23:19,580 --> 00:23:23,280
 Right, that could work with them in a very personalized way to help them learn.

259
00:23:23,280 --> 00:23:26,580
 And I think that this is something that the broader AI community is working on as well.

260
00:23:26,580 --> 00:23:29,880
 And we're thinking about it more kind of like in a Catholic, catechetical context.

261
00:23:29,880 --> 00:23:31,600
 And we see a lot of value there.

262
00:23:31,600 --> 00:23:35,320
 I mean, you think about catechic classes typically, right?

263
00:23:35,320 --> 00:23:38,100
 I mean, you can have 20, 30, 40, 50 students in there.

264
00:23:38,180 --> 00:23:46,100
 And so, you know, the teacher or the priest or whoever is delivering their relative sister, they have a curriculum they have to cover, and they try and cover it.

265
00:23:46,100 --> 00:23:47,320
 They deliver it the best way they can.

266
00:23:47,320 --> 00:23:56,260
 But, you know, a lot of those kids, I'm sure, would really benefit if they had more kind of personalized instruction, which takes into account pedagogically how they learn most optimally, right?

267
00:23:56,920 --> 00:24:02,380
 And I think that's one of the benefits of artificial intelligence, right, is that – and this is something we're working for as we build our voice mode.

268
00:24:02,380 --> 00:24:07,060
 And the idea is that a student can actually interact with a – with Magistram AI via a voice.

269
00:24:07,060 --> 00:24:15,620
 And then Magistram AI will be given a curriculum, will be basically taught – told to instruct that student on the curriculum and then validate their understanding as they work their way through.

270
00:24:16,200 --> 00:24:19,660
 And what's neat about that is that as the AI is interacting with a student, it learns about them.

271
00:24:19,660 --> 00:24:23,400
 It can adapt its pedagogical style and approach to help the student succeed.

272
00:24:23,400 --> 00:24:26,320
 So in that way, you get kind of highly personalized learning.

273
00:24:26,320 --> 00:24:34,640
 And I think that's very exciting, especially when you think about places in the world where it's difficult for them to get access to, you know, to quality teachers or priests or catechists.

274
00:24:34,640 --> 00:24:38,640
 And so I think this is a way to kind of democratize this.

275
00:24:38,640 --> 00:24:44,040
 This is kind of catechesis and ensure it's optimized for every student, which to me is exciting.

276
00:24:44,040 --> 00:24:45,020
 That's fantastic.

277
00:24:45,520 --> 00:24:51,140
 And then, Matthew, you mentioned expanding the Catholic knowledge base, and that was one of the projects for Magistram AI.

278
00:24:51,140 --> 00:24:53,660
 Can you share how you're doing that?

279
00:24:53,660 --> 00:24:55,700
 What does that look like to expand that knowledge base?

280
00:24:55,700 --> 00:25:07,760
 Well, I mean, initially it was working with, you know, some of our collaborators, some of them are priests and professors to kind of figure out what is the primary doctrine that we should be ensuring Magistram AI is referencing.

281
00:25:07,760 --> 00:25:10,480
 So, you know, at first it was very easy, right?

282
00:25:10,480 --> 00:25:14,780
 I mean, it was just, let's just get all the core dogma and the fundamental doctrine in there.

283
00:25:14,840 --> 00:25:17,340
 And then the question is, where do we go from there?

284
00:25:17,340 --> 00:25:20,760
 And so we had kind of two approaches.

285
00:25:20,760 --> 00:25:24,980
 One was consulting with academics and they were sharing with us what they think is most important.

286
00:25:24,980 --> 00:25:36,440
 The other was just listening to the users and kind of monitoring what they're asking about and then evaluating effectively answering the questions and then determining if we didn't think that the answer was sufficient.

287
00:25:36,580 --> 00:25:55,460
 And so that's how expanding the knowledge base, you know, kind of developed is one was if we, if we had a question, the answer wasn't good, needed sources.

288
00:25:55,460 --> 00:26:00,080
 Cool, let's write down, let's go research, do some research and find out if there are some sources that can cover those off.

289
00:26:00,080 --> 00:26:02,820
 Let's prioritize digitizing those and adding them to the knowledge base.

290
00:26:02,820 --> 00:26:04,220
 And that helped a lot.

291
00:26:04,220 --> 00:26:16,800
 And then the other was just talking to professors of different, you know, different kinds, moral and systematic and, and finding out, you know, what are the, what are the key works that would most inform, will be most useful to users that day to day.

292
00:26:16,800 --> 00:26:20,420
 And then of course we started considering what we have used to research this later.

293
00:26:20,420 --> 00:26:28,780
 So anyways, so that, and we realized that every time we, we prioritize and we ingested a new trove of data, the AI just generally got better.

294
00:26:28,780 --> 00:26:31,200
 And I think it, it makes sense.

295
00:26:31,200 --> 00:26:36,360
 I mean, obviously when someone asks a question, the more, the more documents it has to reference, the better the answer, right?

296
00:26:36,360 --> 00:26:45,680
 I mean, I mean, catechism may give a very concise answer, but if it has, you know, five or six different answers and some of those are historical answers from, from previous catechism, it can, it can kind of see a kind of a,

297
00:26:45,680 --> 00:26:49,580
 a, a, a, a broader way of explaining it.

298
00:26:49,580 --> 00:26:55,180
 And I think in some ways that can be useful because what we often find some people may not be intent with the answer, right?

299
00:26:55,180 --> 00:26:59,420
 So they ask a follow-up question and they really, they're asking the same thing, but they're just, they need to express a different way.

300
00:26:59,420 --> 00:27:05,640
 And so when it has access to kind of different kinds of explanations, we found that that really, really helped, helped a lot.

301
00:27:05,640 --> 00:27:10,860
 So, I mean, our, our knowledge base, you know, when we started with 600, it wasn't, we knew it was not sufficient.

302
00:27:10,860 --> 00:27:15,620
 And so we said that one of our main focus, our company, it has to be basically digitized in the patch.

303
00:27:15,620 --> 00:27:18,580
 when the church, and that, that's, that became a secondary mission of ours.

304
00:27:18,580 --> 00:27:24,240
 My first mission being, um, build and scale Catholic AI, uh, second, uh, digitizing the patch when the church.

305
00:27:24,240 --> 00:27:31,360
 And so it wasn't really until we got, I would say past maybe the 8,000 mark that we really started noticing a big difference.

306
00:27:31,520 --> 00:27:38,300
 When we had 8,000 documents and, you know, the one document would be like theoreticon, like, you know, so some of these docs were, were, were, were enormous.

307
00:27:38,300 --> 00:27:43,820
 That we noticed that, that the, the AI was pretty good at finding a number of references to cover off most queries.

308
00:27:43,820 --> 00:27:47,680
 And now I think we're over, you know, uh, approaching 28,000 works.

309
00:27:47,680 --> 00:27:50,640
 And, and hopefully by the end of the summer, uh, we'll be able to double that.

310
00:27:50,640 --> 00:28:02,320
 So what we're looking at now is having the collective works of all the fathers of the church, the doctors of the church, and basically everything, everything that the popes have said, at least, um, uh, pretty comprehensively for the last 120 years.

311
00:28:02,560 --> 00:28:05,780
 And now we're starting to go back into the more ancient popes to include those writings as well.

312
00:28:05,780 --> 00:28:06,540
 Wow.

313
00:28:06,540 --> 00:28:16,040
 And Matthew, um, you know, working, working on, on these very hard problems, what does it make you even more aware of in terms of Catholic knowledge?

314
00:28:16,040 --> 00:28:19,840
 I mean, this continuity, this, you know, this universality at the same time.

315
00:28:19,840 --> 00:28:26,300
 Um, one of the big challenges that I know that, um, a lot of the other major LLMs are, are facing is what, what is objective truth?

316
00:28:26,300 --> 00:28:32,400
 What are you referencing that, you know, and having this, this incredibly high quality of, of, of knowledge of texts that have been,

317
00:28:32,560 --> 00:28:37,300
 worked on for centuries and centuries, what is it, what does it bring to bear?

318
00:28:37,300 --> 00:28:40,220
 You know, what, what does it make even more clear in your eyes now?

319
00:28:40,220 --> 00:28:50,440
 Well, I think, uh, you know, the first thing is the questions that we may think that people have, and we had a lot of expectations.

320
00:28:50,440 --> 00:28:57,660
 What questions people will have, um, are not, are not necessarily questions they ask.

321
00:28:57,660 --> 00:29:00,220
 I mean, that, that was, that was pretty shocking to us.

322
00:29:00,220 --> 00:29:01,220
 We, there's a word for that.

323
00:29:01,280 --> 00:29:02,440
 We call it the long tail.

324
00:29:02,440 --> 00:29:07,100
 And so when we launched matters for me, I, we, we felt fundamental doctrine should be able to cover.

325
00:29:07,100 --> 00:29:12,080
 I think it was because we disfigured at least when we got it started, it'd probably be catechists and teachers and things like that.

326
00:29:12,080 --> 00:29:19,100
 They'd be using matters for my predominantly, but then very quickly, it started getting into the high schools and it was, it was incredible.

327
00:29:19,100 --> 00:29:23,300
 How many people would ask these very personal questions of like, here's something going on in my life.

328
00:29:23,300 --> 00:29:24,080
 What would the church say to me?

329
00:29:24,080 --> 00:29:30,900
 And this caused a bit of a panic for us because that required the LLM to kind of generalize from say first principles to that particular situation.

330
00:29:30,900 --> 00:29:38,620
 And, you know, the early models weren't that intelligent, not, I'm saying intelligence, you know, in quotation marks, they weren't, they weren't very good at that.

331
00:29:38,620 --> 00:29:40,100
 They were okay, but they weren't great.

332
00:29:40,100 --> 00:29:42,080
 And, but they're certainly a lot better now.

333
00:29:43,160 --> 00:29:51,100
 And so one of the, one of the, like key challenges is how do we help the LLM generalize and, or, or should we even be doing this?

334
00:29:51,100 --> 00:29:53,380
 I mean, my initial instinct was this is, we should not be doing this.

335
00:29:53,380 --> 00:29:54,820
 This is, this is, this is too dangerous.

336
00:29:54,820 --> 00:29:58,880
 But then I realized that the questions are going to keep coming.

337
00:29:58,880 --> 00:29:59,860
 They're just not going to come to us.

338
00:29:59,860 --> 00:30:01,180
 They're going to take it to ChatGPT.

339
00:30:01,180 --> 00:30:03,040
 And, and so how comfortable are we with that?

340
00:30:03,040 --> 00:30:03,500
 Right.

341
00:30:03,500 --> 00:30:07,320
 I mean, dude, I mean, at least we're, we're, we're, our objective function fidelity.

342
00:30:07,320 --> 00:30:11,240
 We're going to try to make sure that the AI is faithful, whereas ChatGPT is not going to try, right.

343
00:30:11,240 --> 00:30:16,840
 It'll do its best, of course, but it's going to be wrong a lot more than probably we would if we could, because we're making concerted effort.

344
00:30:16,840 --> 00:30:23,720
 So, you know, as much as, as uncomfortable as, you know, as I was with the prospect, I, we knew that we did something we were just going to have to do.

345
00:30:23,720 --> 00:30:25,060
 We have to find a way to accommodate this.

346
00:30:25,060 --> 00:30:39,500
 And so then we started trying to think through where's the greatest trove of, of knowledge or examples of generalization of church teaching to people's particular situations or societal situations, contextual situations.

347
00:30:40,260 --> 00:30:44,560
 And, and eventually we realized, well, hang on, the popes, that's what the popes do all the time.

348
00:30:44,560 --> 00:30:48,960
 I mean, I mean, like they have, you know, they have homilies, they have general audiences, not just popes, cardinals and things as well.

349
00:30:48,960 --> 00:30:54,380
